    <%# Comparison article %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>Key Differences Between 15-Year and 30-Year Mortgages</h2>
      <p>
        Choosing between a 15-year and 30-year mortgage is one of the most impactful financial decisions you will make as a homeowner. Both loan types use the same amortization formula, but the difference in term length creates dramatically different outcomes for your monthly budget, total interest cost, and wealth-building trajectory. Understanding these trade-offs is essential before signing on the dotted line.
      </p>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
        <table class="min-w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800">
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Factor</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">15-Year Mortgage</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">30-Year Mortgage</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Monthly Payment</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Higher (roughly 40-50% more)</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Lower and more affordable</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Total Interest Paid</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Significantly less (often 50-65% less)</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Much higher over the life of the loan</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Interest Rate</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Typically 0.25-0.75% lower</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Higher rate from the lender</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Equity Building Speed</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Much faster equity accumulation</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Slower, especially in early years</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Cash Flow Flexibility</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Less monthly cash available</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">More room for other investments</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Total Amount Paid</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Lower overall cost of homeownership</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Higher total cost over 30 years</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>When to Choose a 15-Year Mortgage</h2>
      <p>
        A 15-year mortgage is ideal if you have a stable, high income and want to minimize the total cost of your home. Borrowers who are closer to retirement often prefer the shorter term so they can own their home outright before leaving the workforce. If you can comfortably afford the higher monthly payment while still contributing to retirement accounts and maintaining an emergency fund, a 15-year loan is the more cost-effective path. The lower interest rate available on 15-year terms amplifies the savings further. Homeowners who prioritize debt-free living and rapid equity growth will find this option particularly appealing.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>When to Choose a 30-Year Mortgage</h2>
      <p>
        A 30-year mortgage makes sense when you need lower monthly payments to maintain financial flexibility. First-time homebuyers, young professionals, and families with variable incomes often benefit from the reduced monthly obligation. The extra cash flow can be directed toward higher-return investments, emergency savings, or paying down higher-interest debt like credit cards or student loans. In many housing markets, the 30-year term is the only way to keep payments within the recommended 28% of gross income guideline. Remember that a 30-year mortgage does not lock you in for 30 years — you can always make extra payments to pay it off sooner while retaining the safety net of a lower required payment.
      </p>

      <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>
        The right mortgage term depends on your income, financial goals, and risk tolerance. A 15-year mortgage saves you a substantial amount in interest and builds equity at double the speed, but it requires a significantly higher monthly payment. A 30-year mortgage gives you breathing room and flexibility, at the cost of paying more interest over the life of the loan. Use the calculators above to run the numbers with your actual loan amount and rates. For many borrowers, the best strategy is a hybrid approach: take a 30-year mortgage for the lower required payment, then make extra principal payments whenever possible to shorten the effective term.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Is a 15-year mortgage better than a 30-year mortgage?</h3>
      <p>
        A 15-year mortgage saves you significantly on total interest and builds equity faster, but it comes with higher monthly payments. A 30-year mortgage offers lower monthly payments and greater cash flow flexibility. The better option depends on your financial situation, income stability, and long-term goals.
      </p>

      <h3>How much interest do you save with a 15-year mortgage?</h3>
      <p>
        On a $300,000 loan at 6.5%, a 15-year mortgage costs about $134,000 in total interest, while a 30-year mortgage costs about $382,000. That is a savings of roughly $248,000 — nearly the original loan amount — by choosing the shorter term.
      </p>

      <h3>Are interest rates lower on a 15-year mortgage?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, 15-year mortgages typically carry interest rates 0.25% to 0.75% lower than 30-year mortgages. Lenders offer lower rates because shorter loans carry less risk. This rate advantage further increases the total interest savings of the 15-year option.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I afford the higher payments on a 15-year mortgage?</h3>
      <p>
        Financial advisors generally recommend that your total housing costs not exceed 28% of your gross monthly income. If the 15-year payment pushes you above this threshold, a 30-year mortgage may be the safer choice. You can always make extra payments on a 30-year loan to pay it off faster while keeping the flexibility of lower required payments.
      </p>

      <h3>What if I can only afford a 30-year mortgage?</h3>
      <p>
        A 30-year mortgage is a perfectly reasonable choice, especially for first-time buyers or those in high cost-of-living areas. You can reduce total interest by making extra principal payments when you have surplus cash. Even one extra payment per year can shave several years off a 30-year loan and save tens of thousands in interest.
      </p>

